<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
	<title>FAS to RDF Conversion Tool</title>
	<%= stylesheet_link_tag 'scaffold' %>
	</head>
<body>
	<div class='container'>
	<h1>FAS to RDF Conversion Tool</h1>
	<% form_for :convert, :url => { :action => "convert"}, :html =>	{:multipart => true}  do |f| %>
		<quote>
			<p><strong>It’s all about networks.</strong> Of the software that I have used to build
			networks from genetic data, the program “Network” has proven the
			easiest to use and the most intuitive. Unfortunately, Network only
			recognises files in a format known as “RDF”, and I haven’t been able
			to find any software that generates this format.
			</p>

			<p>Fortunately, my other half is a programmer. Enter the FAS to RDF
			converter. Simply select your FAS file (the basic no-frills text
			format generated by GenBank, BioEdit, and a number of other programs).
			The converter will generate an RDF file with the same name. Then you
			can import it into Network, and go nuts.</p>

			<p>Happy networking!</p>

			<p>-Kate</p>

			<p><em>P.S. For ease of error-checking, the converter only recognises
			nucleotide and binary data, not translated amino acid sequences.</em></p>
		</quote>
	  
		<% if notice %>
			<div class='notice'><%= notice %></div>
		<% end %>
	  <p>
    1. Pick a valid FAS file to convert:<br />
    <%= f.file_field :fas_file %>
    </p>
		<p>
			2. Click:<br />
    <input type='submit' value='Convert To RDF' onclick="javascript:document.forms[0].action = '/convert/' +  document.forms[0].elements[1].value.replace('.fas', '.rdf')">
    </p>

  <% end %>
	<div class='credits'>
		Copyright 2010 <a href="http://twitter.com/mipearson">Michael Pearson</a> &amp;
		<a href="http://twitter.com/kate_biscuit">Kate Naughton</a>. Source code available at <a href="http://github.com/mipearson/fas2rdf">a github near you</a>.
	</div>
	</div>
</body>

	